Normalization of the data¶

In [47]:
# It is a good idea to normalize the data first before applying GP Regression becasue
# 1. We cen set mean function to 0 after we normalized the data to simplify computation time
# 2. We are less familar with the exact units working with; different units might result in poor result
x = df.values

# Use the build-in function inside sklearn to normalize the dataframe
min_max_scaler = preprocessing.MinMaxScaler()
x_scaled = min_max_scaler.fit_transform(x)

# Convert the numpy array back to panda dataframe
df_norm = pd.DataFrame(x_scaled)

# The sklean function will normlize all three columns of our dataframe which 
# is not what we desire for the first two columns(engine number and cycle count)
# do not need to be normalized, thus we have to recover their original values
df_norm[0] = df[0]
df_norm[1] = df[1]

# This portion of the code can be better written to be more automated.
# But for the purpose of demonstration it is kept this way.
# Intentionally drop 25%, 50% or 75% of the missing values
# This is done by randomly droppping the X percentage of the dataframe index 
drop_25_index = df_norm.sample(frac=.25).index
drop_50_index = df_norm.sample(frac=.50).index
drop_75_index = df_norm.sample(frac=.75).index

# The index selected above are then dropped from the original dataset
df_drop_25 = df_norm.drop(drop_25_index)
df_drop_50 = df_norm.drop(drop_50_index)
df_drop_75 = df_norm.drop(drop_75_index)

GP 25% Missing Values¶

In [65]:
# Initialize the covariance function(i.e. Kernel function) and the mean function
# Since the data is already normalized, the mean function is just simply set to 0
# By doing so we can expect to have a faster computation time.

# As stated in the report, student decided to use Matern kernel function
# This Matern kernel function is a build in function for pymc3 and it can be 
# executed using the command pm.gp.cov.Matern52(ν, ℓ)
# There are two hyperparameters for Matern function: term Gamma and nu. 


with pm.Model() as model:
    
    # Initialize the piror (i.e inital hyper-parameters) for the kernel function 
    # Initialize the Gamma term(2 hyper-parameters associated with term Gamma)
    ℓ = pm.Gamma("ℓ", alpha=2, beta=1)
    
    # a scaling term is added to the standard kernel function to proive more flexiblity
    # The term eta is set to have a normal distribtuon 
    η = pm.Normal('η', mu=0.4, sigma=0.5)
    
    # Define the covariance function based on the kernel function selected(i.e. Matern kernel)
    # and the term for scaling
    cov = η**2 * pm.gp.cov.Matern52(1, ℓ)
    
    # Define the mean function to be zero all across
    mean_func = pm.gp.mean.Zero()
    
    # Implement GP using the mean function and the covariance function defined above
    gp = pm.gp.Marginal(mean_func = mean_func,cov_func=cov)

    # Introduce a noise term
    # Make the noise term normally distributed
    σ = pm.Normal('σ', mu=0.4, sigma=0.5)
    
    
    y_ = gp.marginal_likelihood("y", X=np.array(df_drop_25[df_drop_25[0]==1].index).reshape(-1,1),\
                                y=df_drop_25[df_drop_25[0]==1][2].values, noise=σ)

    # Use the built in maximum a posteriori function to calculate the 'true' values
    # For the hyper-parameters 
    mp = pm.find_MAP()
100.00% [28/28 00:00<00:00 logp = 26.561, ||grad|| = 120.34]

# Check the finalized parameter values for the kernel function 
# Please note that the values calculated using MAP function will be
# Very close to the true value but it is not the exact one

# Bayesian Inference or integration approach can be used to find the extact 
# Hyper-parameter values. Due to simplicity MAP approach is selected
pd.DataFrame({"Parameter": ["ℓ", "η", "σ"],
              "Value at MAP": [float(mp["ℓ"]), float(mp["η"]), float(mp["σ"])]})

In [57]:



    


# Will predict the first 200 cycle's sensor reading
X_new = np.linspace(0, 200, 200)[:,None]

# Make prediction based on the samples presented
with model:
    # predictions are being made based on the conditional probablity calculated above
    # 5000 samples are selected and the average of all 5000 samples will be the predicted value
    y_pred = gp.conditional("y_pred", X_new, pred_noise=True)
    y_samples = pm.sample_posterior_predictive([mp], vars=[y_pred], samples=5000)



    















    







    

        
      
      100.00% [5000/5000 02:59<00:00]

# The final prediction will be the average value of all 5000 samples
# To find this out a list is created to store this 
gp_25_prediction = list()

# For every cycle 
for sample_no in range( y_samples["y_pred"].shape[1]):
    
    # Calculated the average prediction value and append to the list
    gp_25_prediction.append( y_samples["y_pred"][:,sample_no].mean())

# Change to numpy array back to panda dataframe
gp_25_prediction = np.array(gp_25_prediction)

Accuracy for 75 Percent Missing Values¶












In [41]:



    


# Initialize the covariance function(i.e. Kernel function) and the mean function
# Since the data is already normalized, the mean function is just simply set to 0
# By doing so we can expect to have a faster computation time.

# As stated in the report, student decided to use Matern kernel function
# This Matern kernel function is a build in function for pymc3 and it can be 
# executed using the command pm.gp.cov.Matern52(ν, ℓ)
# There are two hyperparameters for Matern function: term Gamma and nu. 


with pm.Model() as model:
    
    # Initialize the piror (i.e inital hyper-parameters) for the kernel function 
    # Initialize the Gamma term(2 hyper-parameters associated with term Gamma)
    ℓ = pm.Gamma("ℓ", alpha=2, beta=1)
    
    # a scaling term is added to the standard kernel function to proive more flexiblity
    # The term eta is set to have a normal distribtuon 
    η = pm.Normal('η', mu=0.4, sigma=0.5)
    
    # Define the covariance function based on the kernel function selected(i.e. Matern kernel)
    # and the term for scaling
    cov = η**2 * pm.gp.cov.Matern52(1, ℓ)
    
    # Define the mean function to be zero all across
    mean_func = pm.gp.mean.Zero()
    
    # Implement GP using the mean function and the covariance function defined above
    gp = pm.gp.Marginal(mean_func = mean_func,cov_func=cov)

    # Introduce a noise term
    # Make the noise term normally distributed
    σ = pm.Normal('σ', mu=0.4, sigma=0.5)
    
    
    y_ = gp.marginal_likelihood("y", X=np.array(df_drop_75[df_drop_75[0]==1].index).reshape(-1,1),\
                                y=df_drop_75[df_drop_75[0]==1][2].values, noise=σ)

    # Use the built in maximum a posteriori function to calculate the 'true' values
    # For the hyper-parameters 
    mp = pm.find_MAP()



    















    







    

        
      
      100.00% [31/31 00:00<00:00 logp = -6.518, ||grad|| = 4.2778e-05]

In [53]:

df_dummy_75.iloc[np.sort(drop_75_index),2] = 0

df_dummy_50 = df_dummy_50.replace(0,method='ffill')
df_dummy_50 = df_dummy_50.replace(0,method='bfill')
